### E.m.f. from Motion

In electromagnetism, we observe electrical energy converted into kinetic energy using an electric motor. In electromagnetism induction, we can observe, explain, and calculate the electrical energy that is converted from mechanical motion.

#### Electromagnetic induction of straight conductor

To explain why **relative motion** of a conductor and a magnetic field induces an e.m.f., consider a thin straight conductor of length \(L\) moving at a constant speed \(\nu\) in a region of uniform magnetic flux density \(B\) directed normally into the plane of paper as shown. By Fleming's left-hand rule, electrons initially experience a downward magnetic force.

Negative charges accumulate at the lower end, which results in a corresponding region of positive charge at the upper end.

_Inside_ the conductor, a potential difference is induced and results in an electric field down the length of the conductor.

_Outside_ the conductor, it can be regarded as an induced e.m.f. that can drive current around an external circuit.

Steady state is attained when the magnetic force and electric force are balanced. There will be no further charge separation and the induced e.m.f. (\(\varepsilon_{\text{induced}}\)) will remain constant:

\[\begin{split} F_{\text{B}}&=F_{\text{E}}\\ B\not{\psi}\,\widehat{\text{Sh}}&=\not{\varepsilon} \\ B\nu&=\frac{\Delta\nu}{d}=\frac{\varepsilon_{\text{induced} }}{L}\\ \varepsilon_{\text{induced}}&=BL\nu\end{split}\]

**Note**: The equation is true in general for a straight conductor of length \(L\) "cutting" magnetic flux lines but it is not one that we should recall and use. For most questions, we will need to start from basic principles and show how an equation is formed, before applying it.

From the equation, magnitude of \(\varepsilon_{\text{induced}}\) depends on the magnitude of the external magnetic flux density, the length of conductor that is inside the magnetic field, and the speed at which the wire is moving across the field.

